### 10. Transactions `/15`

**✅ Fully Implemented — All critical SPs use explicit transactions**

| Stored Procedure | Isolation Level | What it protects |
|---|---|---|
| `sp_AllocateResource` | `SERIALIZABLE` + `UPDLOCK, ROWLOCK` | Prevents double-allocation of same resource stock |
| `sp_AssignRescueTeam` | `SERIALIZABLE` + `UPDLOCK, ROWLOCK` | Prevents assigning an already-busy team concurrently |
| `sp_MarkTeamBusy` | `BEGIN TRANSACTION` | Atomic status update + audit |
| `sp_CompleteAssignment` | `BEGIN TRANSACTION` + `UPDLOCK, ROWLOCK` | Reads old status, marks complete, conditionally restores team |
| `sp_RecordFinancialTransaction` | `BEGIN TRANSACTION` | Atomic INSERT + audit log |
| `sp_ProcessApproval` | `BEGIN TRANSACTION` | Atomic approval + linked allocation status update |
| `sp_AdmitPatient` | `BEGIN TRANSACTION` | Bed availability check + INSERT Patients + INSERT Admits atomically |

All use `BEGIN TRY / BEGIN CATCH` with `IF @@TRANCOUNT > 0 ROLLBACK; THROW;`.

**In C#:** Controllers call SPs via `DbHelper.ExecuteStoredProcedureNonQuery()` wrapped in `try/catch` that surfaces `TempData["Error"]` to the UI. The transaction boundary lives entirely in SQL Server.

